narrativeContentItems.name: NCI-1
NCI-1.1
narrativeContentItems.text:
• The current study is a randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled, multicenter, Phase 3 study
  • to compare the efficacy and safety of golcadomide plus rituximab, cyclophosphamide,
  • doxorubicin, vincristine, and prednisone (R-CHOP) given in 21-day treatment cycles vs placebo
  • plus R-CHOP in participants with previously untreated high-risk large B-cell lymphoma.
  • Approximately 850 participants will be randomized at a 1:1 ratio to either golcadomide plus R-
  • CHOP or placebo plus R-CHOP. Randomization will be stratified by International Prognostic
  • Index (IPI) score (hazard ratio [HR] 1-2 and 3 vs 4-5) and bulky disease (≥ 7 cm vs < 7 cm). The
  • study will consist of three consecutive periods: screening period, study treatment period and post
  • treatment follow-up period. Study participation for each participant will include a screening
  • period of up to 28 days (4 weeks) followed by 6 cycles (18 weeks) of either golcadomide plus R-
  • CHOP or 6 cycles (18 weeks) of placebo plus R-CHOP in the study treatment period.
  • Subsequently, all participants will move into the post-treatment follow-up period.
  • Please refer to the Investigator’s Brochure for detailed information concerning the available
  • pharmacology, toxicology, drug metabolism, clinical studies, and adverse event profile of the
  • Investigational Product (IP).

narrativeContentItems.name: NCI-1.1.1
narrativeContentItems.text:
• R-CHOP, typically administered for 6 cycles, is the standard therapy for diffuse large B-cell
  • lymphoma (DLBCL). 1 This regimen cures approximately 60% to 70% of patients. In contrast,
  • 30% to 40% of DLBCL patients who are refractory or who relapse following R-CHOP have a
  • poor overall clinical outcome, most of them dying within 2 years despite recent therapeutic
  • advances. 2,3
  • Subsequent lines of therapy given with curative intent still produce drastically decreased rates of
  • long-term disease control while producing cumulative toxicities with each additional systemic or
  • targeted therapy administered. This leaves a large population in need of more efficacious
  • frontline therapies, both to improve cure rates and to avoid further toxicity.
  • Because the greatest likelihood of obtaining a cure occurs in the 1L setting, many attempts have
  • been made to develop new therapies based on the R-CHOP backbone to improve the cure rate. In
  • specific populations, based on IPI or pathological baseline characteristics, a better efficacy
  • associated with dose-dense or dose-intense regimens has been suggested but has not been further
  • confirmed in large, randomized trials. 4,5,6 Several innovative therapies have been developed and
  • tested in large Phase 3 randomized trials in combination with R-CHOP, including proteasome
  • inhibitors7, Bruton’s tyrosine kinase inhibitors 8, immunomodulatory compound9, vascular

10

  • endothelial growth factor inhibitors9F , and second generation anti-CD20 monoclonal
  • antibodies 11. All of these trials failed to demonstrate a significant improvement in the outcome
  • of patients compared with R-CHOP.

  • Recently, the polatuzumab-R-CHP regimen was approved in the United States (US) and
  • European Union (EU) as first-line treatment for DLBCL patients based on findings from the
  • POLARIX study. 12 The study met the primary endpoint, which was progression-free survival
  • (PFS), by demonstrating a 27% reduction in relative risk for progression, relapse, or death
  • compared with R-CHOP. The 2-year PFS rate in the IPI 2-5 population was 76.7% in the
  • experimental arm (polatuzumab-R-CHP) vs 70.2% in the control arm (R-CHOP), an absolute
  • difference of 6.5%. Updated results from the POLARIX study after a longer median follow-up of
  • 3 years continue to show a statistically significant reduction in the risk of progression or death
  • for the experimental combination but without any demonstrated survival benefit (US Food and
  • Drug Administration [FDA], Oncologic Drugs Advisory Committee, United States Prescribing
  • Information). 13
  • By utilizing the IPI prognostic score to predict clinical outcomes in DLBCL, it has been shown
  • that DLBCL patients with high disease risk have worse outcomes after R-CHOP therapy than the
  • overall DLBCL patient population. The progression-free survival (PFS) in the high-intermediate
  • (IPI = 3) and high-risk (IPI = 4-5) IPI patient population treated with R-CHOP is significantly
  • lower, with a 2-year PFS rate of approximately 58% to70% compared with 85% to 90% in patients
  • with low (IPI = 0-1) or low-intermediate (IPI = 2) IPI risk. 14 Additionally, the double-hit
  • molecular subtype and high-grade B-cell lymphomas (HGBLs, not otherwise specified [NOS])
  • typically have an aggressive clinical course and are responsible for early relapses and dismal
  • outcomes. 15 Despite attempts to intensify R-CHOP, there is still no optimal treatment approach
  • for patients with these aggressive histologic subtypes.
  • Outcome of patients with DLBCL is shown to be influenced by clinical factors, including high
  • lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) and bulky disease. 16, 17 In a recent publication, it was shown that
  • patients with high LDH and/or bulky disease at diagnosis (LDH ≥ 1.3 x upper limit of normal
  • [ULN] and bulky disease defined as single lesion of ≥ 7 cm in maximum diameter of the largest
  • tumor lesion) appear to have an inferior outcome that extends to lower IPI scores, such as IPI 1
  • and 2, hereafter referred to as high-risk IPI 1-2. 18 This high risk IPI 1-2 population has a 2-year
  • event-free survival (EFS) rate (71.6%) that is similar to the 2-year EFS rate of the IPI 3
  • population (70.7%).

narrativeContentItems.name: NCI-1.1.2
narrativeContentItems.text:
• Stricter eligibility criteria in the last decades with consistent exclusion of patients with rapidly
  • progressive or symptomatic disease not being able to perform screening procedures has been
  • identified as a cause of selection bias that limits the generalizability of clinical trials to the general
  • DLBCL population. 19, 20, 21 Up to a quarter of patients may be excluded from trial participation
  • on the basis of organ function alone. 22 Patients typically excluded from clinical studies with novel
  • combinations due to selection bias have worse outcomes compared with the ones included with
  • similar disease characteristics. 23
  • In the CA0731020 study, organ function-based criteria have been reviewed and tailored to
  • golcadomide’s safety characteristics. Where permitted by the safety profile of the study treatment,

  • general eligibility cutoffs have been relaxed and have been removed for disease–related organ
  • function derangements. Temporizing pre-phase measures including corticosteroids and rituximab
  • are allowed to reverse disease–related organ function impairment before randomization.

narrativeContentItems.name: NCI-1.1.3
narrativeContentItems.text:
• In conclusion, the dismal prognosis of 30% to 40% of DLBCL patients who are refractory or
  • who relapse following R-CHOP despite recent additions in the frontline setting points towards a
  • therapeutic area of unmet medical need and warrants the evaluation of new treatment strategies
  • to improve survival outcomes. An enrichment strategy with careful attention to laboratory-based
  • criteria and expedited enrollment procedures is warranted to minimize selection bias in Phase 3
  • studies. Given its properties and the promising activity seen in its early phase of development,
  • the addition of golcadomide to the currently used induction therapy is a rational approach with
  • the potential to improve outcomes in this disease setting.
  • Based on the above, the Sponsor proposes this randomized Phase 3 study of golcadomide in
  • combination with R-CHOP vs placebo in combination with R-CHOP in patients with previously
  • untreated high risk large B-cell lymphoma (LBCL).

narrativeContentItems.text:

  • anticipated adverse events (AEs) of golcadomide may be found in the Investigator’s Brochure.

narrativeContentItems.name: NCI-1.2.1
narrativeContentItems.text:
• Golcadomide has exhibited multiple pharmacological activities including single-agent
  • antiproliferative effects with pre-clinical data, showing potent induction of apoptosis in DLBCL
  • cell lines as well as potent immunomodulation of normal lymphocytes. In the clinical setting,
  • golcadomide has demonstrated promising efficacy in combination with R-CHOP including in
  • high-risk patients.
  • The oral formulation and ease of administration of golcadomide without dietary restrictions
  • make it a highly attractive agent to be investigated in combination therapy for the treatment of
  • LBCL.
  • MRD negativity is a key secondary endpoint in this study, and the ctDNA samples collected may
  • improve our understanding of drug efficacy. Additional exploratory biomarkers will be collected
  • throughout the study using blood, tumor, and saliva samples. These biomarkers will improve
  • understanding of the mechanism of action of, or could predict response or toxicity to, the IPs and
  • are expected to further add to the characterization of the safety profiles of golcadomide and
  • improve participant safety.

narrativeContentItems.name: NCI-1.2.2
narrativeContentItems.text:
• The safety and tolerability profile of lenalidomide has been well characterized through its use in
  • lymphoma. Given the similar mechanism of action and available clinical data, the safety and
  • tolerability profile of golcadomide is anticipated to have common features with that of
  • lenalidomide and other next generation CELMoDs.

  • This extensive prior experience with lenalidomide in combination with available golcadomide
  • safety, PK/pharmacodynamic (PD) data from the FIH CC-99282-NHL-001 study and CC-220-
  • DLBCL-001 study have been used to plan the safety monitoring and risk mitigation schedule of
  • golcadomide in this study.
  • The CA0731020 study has a robust monitoring schedule of participants’ safety throughout
  • frequent visits during treatment and follow-up period, and participants are encouraged to contact
  • the investigator if an intercurrent illness develops between study visits.
  • A Data Monitoring Committee (DMC) will meet regularly to monitor safety throughout the
  • duration of the study. The DMC will provide an integrated assessment of the available safety
  • data and preliminary efficacy information during the study. If such assessment suggests that the
  • risk/benefit profile of the study has become unfavorable to participants, the Sponsor will pause
  • enrollment and/or treatment until further evaluation of data, and interaction with Health
  • Authority(ies) can take place on potential actions. Such actions may include (but are not limited
  • to) study continuation, substantial amendment, or termination of the study.
  • Human safety data have shown all compounds to be safe and tolerable at the proposed study dose
  • levels (DL) for golcadomide and at the approved doses and schedules of R-CHOP. However,
  • actual clinical risks of the new combinations are not completely known, and some clinical risks
  • can be anticipated based on overlapping toxicities of these drugs and as noted in the
  • Investigator’s Brochure for golcadomide, and country-specific package inserts for rituximab and
  • the CHOP components. Based on findings from toxicity studies, experience with earlier
  • generation immunomodulatory agents and golcadomide studies, the following safety monitoring
  • is to be implemented in order to mitigate risks to study participants:

narrativeContentItems.name: NCI-1.2.4
narrativeContentItems.text:
• Golcadomide is a thalidomide analog, and thalidomide is a known human teratogen that causes
  • severe life-threatening birth defects. Embryofetal developmental toxicity studies have been
  • conducted with golcadomide in rats and rabbits. Golcadomide was considered a selective
  • developmental teratogen in these studies. If golcadomide is taken during pregnancy, a teratogenic
  • effect in humans is possible. Male and female participants participating in golcadomide studies

narrativeContentItems.text:
• The study is designed as a randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled, multicenter, Phase 3
  • study to compare the efficacy and safety of golcadomide plus R-CHOP vs placebo plus R-CHOP
  • in participants with previously untreated high-risk large B-cell lymphoma. Approximately 850
  • participants will be randomized at a 1:1 ratio to either golcadomide plus R-CHOP or placebo plus
  • R-CHOP. Randomization will be stratified by IPI score (HR 1-2 and 3 vs 4-5) and bulky disease
  • (≥7 cm vs. < 7 cm).
  • The study will consist of three consecutive periods: screening period, study treatment period and
  • post treatment follow-up period. Study participation for each participant will include a screening
  • period of up to 28 days (4 weeks) followed by 6 cycles (18 weeks) of either golcadomide plus R-
  • CHOP or 6 cycles (18 weeks) of placebo plus R-CHOP in the study treatment period.
  • Subsequently, all patients will move into the post-treatment follow-up period.
  • The screening period for eligibility determination will begin after the participant signs the
  • informed consent form. During the screening period, participants will undergo safety and other
  • assessments, including local pathology confirmation of diagnosis and radiologic assessments of
  • measurable disease (Lugano, Appendix 9). Following confirmation of eligibility, participants will
  • undergo randomization to either the experimental (golcadomide + R-CHOP) or control (placebo +
  • R-CHOP) arm in a 1:1 ratio.
  • The Study treatment period begins with Cycle 1 Day 1 dosing. Participants will receive protocol-
  • specified treatments for 6 cycles administered every 21 days. Treatment will continue to
  • completion of 6 cycles; or until disease progression as assessed by the investigator; unacceptable
  • toxicity; death; or withdrawal of consent, whichever occurs first.
  • The study treatment period ends when the participant has received the last dose of either
  • golcadomide or placebo as part of the last treatment cycle. The end of treatment (EOT) safety
  • follow-up visit will occur at the completion of safety follow-up period (28 days from last dose).
  • PET scan assessment as part of the EOT efficacy follow-up will be performed 6-8 weeks from last
  • dose.
  • The post treatment follow-up period for each participant begins immediately after their EOT Safety
  • follow-up or early treatment discontinuation visit and ends at the later of 3 years from the last
  • randomized patient’s last treatment date, date of 265th primary PFS event being observed.
  • All participants will be followed from randomization, for first progression, subsequent
  • progressions, subsequent anti-lymphoma therapies, and overall survival (OS), until the target 265
  • PFS events have been accrued or the last randomized patient has been followed for at least 3 years
  • from the last dose of treatment, whichever occurs later.
  • The PFS primary analysis is expected to be at ~46.7 months from the first randomization by power
  • simulation, including an enrollment period of approximately 26.6 months. The expected total study
  • duration is expected to be ~66.8 months (26.6 months of accrual + 4.2 months of treatment + 36
  • months minimum follow-up).

narrativeContentItems.text:
This randomized, Phase 3 study has been designed as an add-on placebo-controlled study where golcadomide has been added to the established standard of care (SOC), which is R-CHOP in the experimental arm while placebo in combination with R-CHOP will comprise the control arm.

For almost 2 decades, R-CHOP chemotherapy has remained the standard of care for untreated LBCL patients. The chemotherapy regimen and dosing for CHOP was established in the 1970s, and the addition of the anti-CD20 monoclonal antibody rituximab (R) was approved in 2006 based on 3 large, randomized studies, which consistently demonstrated a survival benefit in favor of the

  • CHOP in the 1L setting. Unfortunately, all failed to demonstrate improved outcomes compared to
  • R-CHOP alone. Recently, however polatuzumab in combination with rituximab,
  • cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin and prednisone (pola-R-CHP) was approved in the US and EU
  • for the treatment of adult patients with untreated DLBCL, NOS or HGBL, and an IPI score of 2 or

  • greater based on the results from the Phase 3 POLARIX study. Additionally, based on these results,
  • pola-R-CHP was recently made a category 1 recommendation alongside R-CHOP for the first-line
  • treatment of patients with LBCL in the National Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN)
  • guidelines. 28
  • R-CHOP is considered the most appropriate backbone for the control arm as it allows for this
  • Phase 3 study to be designed in a double-blind placebo-controlled fashion, which will reduce
  • investigator and patient bias and optimally capture the total pharmacological effect of
  • golcadomide. As a result, this add-on study design will result in the most robust and direct
  • assessment of the safety and efficacy of golcadomide in patients with untreated LBCL without
  • confounding factors, as both the control and investigational arm will share the same R-CHOP
  • backbone.
  • Moreover, since this is a global study and in order to reduce treatment variability across
  • geographical areas, the universally accepted R-CHOP has been selected as the sole control for
  • Study CA0731020.

narrativeContentItems.name: NCI-3.2.1
narrativeContentItems.text:
• Justification of Stratification Factors
  • Randomization in this study will be stratified by IPI score (HR 1-2 and 3 vs. 4-5) and bulky disease
  • (≥7 cm vs. < 7 cm).
  • The IPI score is a standard tool for risk stratification and is a widely accepted and useful predictor
  • of outcomes. As shown by Maurer et al, the presence of bulky disease and/or very high LDH at
  • diagnosis can identify a high-risk subset of participants with IPI 1-2 who have similar outcomes
  • to participants with IPI 3. Therefore, the IPI 3 group will be stratified together with HR patients
  • with IPI 1-2 against the IPI 4-5 group, which typically has the worst prognosis.
  • Despite different cutoffs, bulky disease has previously been shown to have prognostic
  • significance.17, 29 In the CA0731020 study, bulky disease, to pre-defined maximum tumor
  • diameter of 7 cm or greater, will be used for stratification purposes.

narrativeContentItems.name: NCI-3.2.2
narrativeContentItems.text:
• The primary endpoint for this study is progression-free survival (PFS) defined as the time from
  • randomization to the first observation of documented disease progression as assessed by the
  • Investigator based on the Lugano response criteria59 or death due to any cause, whichever occurs
  • first. Since this is a double-blind study, the primary endpoint will be assessed by the Investigator.
  • A review performed by IRAC will be the basis for efficacy calculations of the key secondary
  • endpoint of CMR and secondary endpoint of PFS by IRAC.
  • PFS is considered as an acceptable primary endpoint for registrational Phase 3 trials by European
  • Medicines Agency 30 and FDA 31 and correlates well with overall survival in 1L DLBCL.

    • Rationale for Investigational Trial Intervention Dose and Regimen Golcadomide will be administered orally at the dose of 0.4 mg once daily for 7 consecutive days for 6 cycles in combination with R-CHOP in 21-day cycles in the CA0731020 study.

Golcadomide in ascending doses and various schedules (5 days on/7 days off, 7 days on/14 days off, 14 days on/28 days off) was first explored in the ongoing First-in-Human CC-99282-NHL- 001 study, with the aim to evaluate the safety and activity of golcadomide monotherapy and in combination with other anti-lymphoma agents in participants with R/R NHL. In the escalation part

  • (Part A), golcadomide monotherapy demonstrated promising anti-tumor activity in participants
  • with R/R NHL with an ORR of 43% (17/40) at the 2 schedules selected for dose expansion (7/14
  • and 14/28-day schedule). Upon reviewing the safety, PK, and PD data, the SRC recommended
  • exploration of 2 doses (0.2 mg and 0.4 mg) in Part B (dose expansion) with a goal of defining the
  • dose that provides the optimal balance between safety and efficacy. In the dose-expansion part,
  • golcadomide combined with rituximab showed promising efficacy in heavily pre-treated patients
  • with R/R DLBCL (n=26), with a response rate of 42%, including CR rate of 19%. The overall
  • response rate and complete response rate were greater for participants in the 0.4 mg arm compared
  • to the 0.2 mg arm (55% vs 33% and 27% vs 13%, respectively). The rate of Grade 3/4 neutropenia
  • was 50% and thrombocytopenia 11%. Based on the safety, efficacy, and PK/PD from the CC-
  • 99282-NHL-001 study, the 0.2 mg and 0.4 mg doses of golcadomide given on a 7-day or 10-day
  • schedule were determined to be the optimal doses to explore in combination with R-CHOP in
  • Study CC-220-DLBCL-001.
  • Golcadomide has been further evaluated in the Phase 1b CC-220-DLBCL-001 study in
  • combination with R-CHOP in patients with untreated high-risk large B-cell lymphomas including
  • DLBCL patients. In the CC-220-DLBCL-001 study, as of the 10-Oct-2023 data cutoff, a total of
  • 78 patients (28 in the dose escalation and 50 in the randomized dose expansion) were treated with
  • golcadomide in combination with R-CHOP.
  • In the dose escalation, the following golcadomide dose levels were explored:
  • DL-1: 0.2 mg D1-7 every 21 days (Q21D) (n = 11)
  • DL1: 0.4 mg D1-7 Q21D (n = 11)
  • DL2: 0.4 mg D1-10 Q21D (n = 6). This DL was discontinued per SRC recommendation due to
  • toxicity.
  • In the dose expansion, a total of 50 participants were randomized in a 1:1 fashion between DL-1
  • (N = 24) and DL1 (N = 26) with the goal of identifying the optimal Phase 3 dose.
  • The justification from safety, efficacy, PK-PD, and exposure-response (E-R) data are summarized
  • as follows:
  • Safety: Golcadomide in combination with R-CHOP is generally well tolerated in participants with
  • previously untreated aggressive B-cell lymphoma at the selected Phase 3 dose. Grade 3/4
  • toxicities were primarily hematological in nature and were manageable with standard
  • supportive care and other symptomatic measures. The most common Grade 3/4 treatment-
  • emergent adverse events were neutropenia (89.2%) and thrombocytopenia (59.5%) while
  • 24.3% of patients experienced febrile neutropenia. The preserved relative dose intensities
  • (RDI) of golcadomide and key R-CHOP components indicate that golcadomide combines well
  • with R-CHOP and does not compromise the delivery of curative therapy (median RDI > 97%
  • for golcadomide, cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, vincristine). Preserved dose intensity has
  • consistently been identified as a critical factor influencing outcomes in DLBCL. 32
  • Efficacy: A high EOT CMR rate was observed at the selected dose in the efficacy-evaluable
  • population (n = 29/33, ORR=88%, CMR = 88%). A subset of 27 subjects at the selected phase
  • 3 dose were considered high risk (high risk subjects were IPI 3-5 and IPI 1-2 subjects with
  • LDH ≥ 1.3 x ULN and/or bulky disease, defined as a single lesion of ≥ 7 cm in maximum

  • diameter of the largest tumor lesion). In line with the overall population, high risk subjects had
  • a high EOT CMR (n = 24/27, ORR=89%, CMR = 89%). Rates for MRD at EOT in the efficacy
  • evaluable population using the PhasED-Seq assay were 93% (14/15) at the selected dose and

33,34

  • 74% for historical R-CHOP or R-CHOP-like cohorts.32F The high rate of EOT MRD at the
  • selected dose exceeded the historical benchmarks for R-CHOP and was in line with the clinical
  • responses observed, supporting 0.4 mg D1-7 as the selected dose for the Phase 3 study.
  • Importantly, EOT CMR and MRD negativity have been shown to correlate strongly with
  • survival in patients with newly diagnosed DLCBL. 34
  • PK-PD, E-R: In line with the clinical observations, preliminary PK and PK-PD modeling
  • suggested that a higher exposure and deeper Ikaros degradation can be achieved at the 0.4 mg
  • dose level in comparison with the 0.2 mg dose level at the 7/21 schedule. In addition, the
  • preliminary E-R modeling analyses suggest a positive relationship between exposure and CMR
  • with desired efficacy achieved at the golcadomide exposure, corresponding to the 0.4 mg dose
  • level. With the exception of Grade 4 thrombocytopenia, no obvious E-R trends were found for
  • endpoints, including Grade 3+ neutropenia, any grade febrile neutropenia, and AEs leading to
  • golcadomide modification.
  • Based on the overall manageable safety profile, the promising efficacy with very high CMR rate,
  • and ctDNA clearance at EOT, and available PK-PD data, 0.4 mg D1-7 has been selected as the
  • golcadomide dose and schedule for the Phase 3 study.

Overdose, as defined for this protocol, refers to golcadomide/Placebo and R-CHOP dosing only.

For this study, any dose of golcadomide/placebo, rituximab, cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, vincristine, or prednisone greater than 15% over the protocol-specified dose within 1 treatment cycle period will be considered an overdose, regardless of any associated AEs or sequelae.

On a schedule or frequency basis, an overdose is defined as anything more frequent than the protocol-required schedule or frequency.

In the event of an overdose, the Investigator should:

Closely monitor the participant for AEs/SAEs and laboratory test result abnormalities as a result of overdosing.

Complete data about drug administration, including any overdose, regardless of whether the overdose was accidental or intentional, accurately in the CRF.

Overdoses that meet the regulatory definition of an SAE will be reported as SAEs (See Section 9.2).

Following golcadomide/placebo overdose, decisions regarding dose interruptions or modifications will be made by the investigator in consultation with the Medical Monitor based on the clinical evaluation of the participant. For modification following any of the approved R-CHOP components, please refer to the respective label of individual component.

• An Interactive Response Technology (IRT) system will be employed to accomplish
  • randomization, to record prespecification of optional consolidation radiotherapy, and to manage
  • participant medications.
  • Before the study is initiated, or once the site and user information is provided to the IRT vendor,
  • users at each investigative site will receive log-in information and directions on how to access the
  • IRT system. At the time of the screening visit, after informed consent is obtained, the investigative
  • site will access the IRT system for assignment of a participant number for each participant. The
  • participant number is assigned sequentially by the system and will be unique across all sites. The

999

1000

will be given a new participant number.

1001

The patient identification number (PID) will ultimately comprise the site number and participant

1002

number. For example, the first participant screened (ie, enrolled) at Site Number 1 will have a PID

1003

1004

6.8.2 Randomisation

1006

Once the participant is determined eligible, the investigator or designee will access the IRT within

1007

the 28-day screening period to obtain the randomized treatment assignment for the participant. All

1008

participants will be centrally randomized using IRT in a 1:1 ratio to receive either Golcadomide +

1009

R-CHOP or placebo + R-CHOP according to a computer-generated randomization schedule. The

1010

randomization lists will be generated by the Sponsor using a permuted block design within each

1011

combination of stratification factors as follows:

1012

International Prognostic Index score (IPI 1-2 and 3 vs 4 and 5).

1013

Presence of bulky disease: ≥ 7.0 cm (bulky) vs < 7.0 cm (non-bulky).

1014

After randomization, at subsequent visits, when new treatment kits need to be provided, the

1015

investigative site will access the IRT to obtain the kit number assigned to the participant.

1016

In the event of any dose reduction in any component of study treatment for a participant, the site

1017

1018

accordingly.

1019

6.8.3 Blinding

1020

Study CA0731020 is a double-blind study. Access to treatment codes will be restricted from all

1021

site and Sponsor personnel and participants prior to database lock for the primary PFS analysis

1022

with exceptions as specified below.

1023

Randomization schedules will be shipped directly to a pharmacist or other individual(s) who will

1024

be responsible for the dispensing of blinded study intervention. This (these) individual(s) will be

1025

unblinded to study intervention identification but will not be involved in any other aspect of study

1026

conduct. The randomization schedules will be maintained in a secure location with access limited

1027

to authorized personnel. The treatment assignment will not be recorded on the Case Report Form

1028

(CRF).

1029

6.8.4 Emergency Unblinding at the Site

1030

Blinding of study intervention assignment is critical to the integrity of this clinical study. However,

1031

in the event of a pregnancy, medical emergency, or unexpected death in an individual participant

1032

in which knowledge of the Investigational Product (IP) is critical, the blind for that participant may

1033

be broken by the investigator. The participant’s safety takes priority over any other considerations

1034

in determining whether a treatment assignment should be unblinded.

1035

Before breaking the blind of an individual participant’s treatment, the investigator should

1036

determine that the unblinded information is necessary (ie, that it will alter the participant’s

1037

immediate management). In many cases, particularly when the emergency is clearly not related to

1038

the IP, the problem may be properly managed by assuming that the participant is receiving the IP.

1039

It is highly desirable that the decision to unblind treatment assignment be discussed with the

1040

Medical Monitor, but the investigator always has ultimate authority for the decision to unblind.

1041

The actual task of unblinding can be delegated by the investigator to a designee assigned the task

1042

on the Delegation of Authority form. The Principal Investigator or appointed designee should only

1043

initiate individual participant unblinding after the decision to unblind the participant has been

1044

documented on the appropriate study status page of the CRF.

1045

For this study, the method of unblinding for emergency purposes is blind break (IRT). The IRT

1046

will be programmed with blind-breaking instructions. In case of an emergency, the investigator

1047

has the sole responsibility for determining whether unblinding of a participant’s intervention

1048

assignment is warranted. Participant safety must always be the first consideration in making such

1049

a determination. If the investigator decides that unblinding is warranted, the investigator should

1050

make every effort to contact the Sponsor prior to unblinding a participant’s intervention

1051

assignment unless doing so could delay emergency treatment of the participant. If a participant’s

1052

intervention assignment is unblinded, the Sponsor must be notified within 24 hours after breaking

1053

the blind. The date and reason that the blind was broken must be recorded in the source

1054

documentation and CRF, as applicable.

1055

Please consult the IRT manual for further information on how to unblind a participant.

1056

In cases of accidental unblinding, contact the Medical Monitor and ensure that every attempt is

1057

made to minimize additional disclosure and the impact of unblinding.

1058

Any request to unblind a participant for non-emergency purposes should be discussed with the

1059

Medical Monitor.

1061

1062

1063

intervention.

1073

1074

1077

6.10.3.1 Growth Factors and Transfusions of Blood and Blood Products

1117

Primary prophylaxis with granulocyte colony stimulating factor (G-CSF) against neutropenia is

1118

mandatory at each cycle. Mandatory G-CSF (from Day 5 to Day 13) or pegylated (peg)-G-CSF (at

1119

Day 2) will be given at each cycle for all participants. G-CSF administration may continue beyond

1120

the mandatory days until recovery of neutrophils prior to start of next treatment cycle.

1121

Other growth factors (eg, erythropoietin) or additional G-CSF may be prescribed at any time

1122

during the treatment and follow-up periods at the investigator’s discretion once a participant has

1123

experienced cytopenic or myelosuppressive events.

1124

Subjects enrolled in countries where peg-G-CSF is commercially available will obtain

1125

commercially available product through their local hospital pharmacy or licensed distributor. The

1126

Sponsor will provide peg-G-CSF for countries where supplies are not commercially available, or

1127

not readily available, or not provided per regulation.

1128

6.10.3.2 Thromboembolic Risk or Thromboembolic Events

1129

Based on a mechanism of action that may be similar to other CRBN-binding compounds where

1130

treated participants have increased risk to develop thromboembolic events, participants and

1131

physicians are advised to be observant for the signs and symptoms of thromboembolism.

1132

Thromboembolism prophylaxis is mandatory for all participants. Anticoagulant options for VTE

1133

prophylaxis for ambulatory medical oncology patients include direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs)

1134

(eg, apixaban, rivaroxaban) and low-molecular-weight heparins (LMWHs) (eg, dalteparin and

1135

enoxaparin); see Table 7.7.1.3-1.

1136

6.10.3.3 Infusion Reaction Prophylaxis

1137

Premedication consisting of acetaminophen and an antihistamine should be administered before

1138

each rituximab infusion (refer to the current local rituximab prescribing information). Steroids may

1139

also be administered before the start of the rituximab infusion according to institutional practice.

1140

Surveillance measures during and after infusion of rituximab should be applied as recommended

1141

by the manufacturer and current guidelines.

1142

6.10.3.4 Tumor Lysis Syndrome Prophylaxis

1143

Risk factors for tumor lysis syndrome (TLS) must be evaluated during screening. These include,

1144

but are not restricted to, aggressive histologies, spontaneous TLS, high white blood cell (WBC)

1145

count (> 25 × 109/L), massive bone marrow involvement, bulky disease, renal involvement, or

1146

renal insufficiency.

1147

Participants who are considered at risk of TLS must receive adequate tumor lysis prophylaxis with

1148

rigorous hydration and uricostatics (eg, allopurinol or febuxostat if intolerant to allopurinol),

1149

starting 48 to 72 hours prior to the start of golcadomide. Uricolytic drugs (eg, rasburicase) can be

1150

indicated. Hydration (either orally or IV) must be adapted to risk factors, age, clinical status, and

1151

evolution. Frequency of clinical and electrolytes monitoring should be adapted.

1152

Specifically for participants with rapidly progressing disease considered for prephase regimen with

1153

corticosteroids in combination with rituximab, adequate tumor lysis prophylaxis must start 48 to

1154

72 hours prior to rituximab administration.

1155

Treatment of TLS includes correction of electrolyte abnormalities, monitoring renal function and

1156

fluid balance, and administering supportive care, including dialysis as indicated. Investigators are

1157

to exercise clinical judgment as to whether more frequent serum chemistry monitoring may be

1158

appropriate.

1169

Antiplatelet therapy (aspirin or other) and warfarin are not permitted as VTE prophylaxis in this

1170

study.

1171

Use DOACs cautiously in patients with compromised renal or liver function; see respective labels.

1172

VTE prophylaxis should be used for the duration of study treatment until the end of the 28-day

1173

follow-up period (washout period). Longer periods of treatment should be considered only if

1174

the risk(s) identified at screening persist.

1175

Management of Anticoagulation in Patients with Chemotherapy-induced

1176

Thrombocytopenia

1177

Thrombocytopenia is a common occurrence in patients with cancer who are receiving prophylactic

1178

anticoagulation for cancer-associated thrombosis. Generally, anticoagulation is considered safe

1179

with platelet counts ≥ 50,000/μL. The risk of bleeding is thought to increase as platelet counts

1180

decline below this threshold. Although withholding VTE prophylaxis should be considered when

1181

PLT counts drop < 50,000/μL, for high-risk patients or ongoing VTE, prophylactic anticoagulation

1182

may be appropriate even if PLT count is as low as 25,000/μL. Clinical judgment should be

1183

exercised, and institutional guidelines should be considered in such cases. Investigators are advised

1184

to discuss these cases with the Medical Monitor.

1185

General Contraindications to Prophylactic Anticoagulation

1186

Active bleeding

1187

Thrombocytopenia (platelet count < 50,000/μL or clinical judgment)

1188

Underlying hemorrhagic coagulopathy

1189

Interventional procedures, eg, lumbar puncture or other spine procedure (Refer to institutional-

1190

specific anesthesia practice guidelines, if available.)

1191

Current or previous heparin-induced thrombocytopenia (contraindication for LMWH)

1192

NSAIDs for anti-inflammatory/analgetic purposes during the treatment period should generally

1193

be avoided. Clinical judgment is advised.

1194

6.11 Concomitant Therapy

1195

Over the course of this study, additional medications may be required to manage aspects of the

1196

disease state of the participants, including side effects from trial treatments or disease progression.

1197

Supportive care, including, but not limited to, antiemetic medications, may be administered at the

1198

discretion of the investigator.

1199

All concomitant treatments, including blood and blood products, used from 28 days prior to first

1200

dose of IP until 28 days after the last dose of IP, must be reported on the electronic Case Report

1201

Form (eCRF).

1202

Participants must check with study personnel before initiating the use of prescribed or over-the-

1203

counter medications during the study. Medication doses and treatment regimens should remain

1204

generally stable throughout the course of the study.

1205

In the event a participant requires a surgical or invasive procedure during the course of the study,

1206

the Sponsor Medical Monitor or designee must be contacted to discuss whether or not the

1207

participant is eligible to continue.

1208

6.11.1 Prohibited Concomitant Therapy

1209

Participants must be instructed not to take any medications, including over-the-counter products,

1210

without first consulting with the investigator.

1211

The following medications are considered prohibited concomitant medications during the

1212

study.The Sponsor must be notified if a participant receives any of these during the study.

1213
  • Any investigational therapy

1214
  • Any anticancer therapy, including chemotherapy, radiotherapy (except palliative

1215

radiotherapy), immunotherapy, biologic, or hormonal therapy for cancer treatment

1216
  • Immunosuppressive medications including, but not limited to, systemic corticosteroids at

1217

doses exceeding 10 mg/day of prednisone or equivalent. Use of immunosuppressive

1218

medications for the management of golcadomide-related AEs or in participants with

1219

contrast allergies is acceptable

1220
  • Use of corticosteroids for anti-CD20 mAb preinfusion and postinfusion or in order to treat

1221

tumor flare reaction is acceptable. In addition, use of inhaled, topical, intranasal

1222

corticosteroids, or local steroid injection (eg, intra-articular injection) is permitted.

1223

Temporary use of corticosteroids for concurrent illnesses (eg, food allergies, CT scan

1224

contrast hypersensitivity, pneumonia) are acceptable upon discussion and agreement with

1225

the Medical Monitor.

1226
  • Live vaccines are not permitted to be administered to participants in this trial. Killed or

1227

inactivated vaccines, such as an injectable annual influenza vaccine, are allowed.

1228
  • Live COVID-19 vaccines should generally not be administered to a participant during the

1229

study, including the treatment and safety follow-up period. Live vaccines are defined as

1230

those that are capable of transmitting infectious severe acute respiratory syndrome

1231

coronavirus 2 or other viruses. If it cannot be determined whether or not the vaccine is live,

1232

it is recommended that the vaccine not be administered until it is confirmed that there is no

1233

risk of viral infectivity within the participant. If a participant has received a live COVID-

1234

19 vaccine prior to screening, enrollment should be delayed until the impact of the vaccine

1235

is stabilized, unless a delay would compromise patient health.

1236
  • Medications that are strong inhibitors or inducers of CYP3A4/5 are prohibited. Of note,

1237

any antibiotics/antifungals listed as strong inhibitors or inducers of CYP3A4/5 should be

1238

avoided and replaced by alternate treatment. In general, azole antifungals such as

1239

itraconazole, as well as antibiotics clarithromycin and rifampin should be avoided. Also,

1240

grapefruit, St. John’s Wort, and related products are prohibited while participating in this

1241

study. Please refer to Table 7.7.2-1 for a list of medications that are strong inhibitors and

1242

Table 7.7.2-2 for inducers of CYP3A4/5. Please note this list is not exhaustive. If there are

1243

any questions regarding whether a medication is a strong CYP3A4/5 inhibitor or inducer,

1244

please contact the study Medical Monitor or designee.

Phototoxicity

1248

Golcadomide absorbs ultraviolet (UV) light between the frequencies of 290 and 700 nm and could

1249

distribute to the skin and eyes. In the in vitro assay, golcadomide demonstrated potential for

1250

phototoxicity. As a precautionary measure, it is recommended that participants avoid prolonged

1251

exposure to UV light, wear protective clothing and sunglasses, and use UV blocking topical

1252

preparations while taking golcadomide and for 28 days after the last dose.

1253 6.11.2 Permitted Concomitant Therapy

1254

Therapies considered necessary for the participant’s well-being may be administered at the

1255

discretion of the investigator. See Section 6.10.3 for required non-investigational intervention. See

1256

Section 6.10.1 for optional pre-phase treatment information.

1257

6.11.2.1 CNS Prophylaxis

1258

Participants at high risk for CNS involvement, as defined in the National Comprehensive Cancer

1259

Network (NCCN) guidelines and per the CNS evaluation performed during screening, should

1260

receive CNS lymphoma prophylaxis treatment with intrathecal drugs (eg, IT methotrexate and/or

1261

cytarabine) per NCCN guidelines or per institutional standards. Alternatively, IV CNS

1262

prophylaxis, for example with high-dose methotrexate, is permitted if planned before the

1263

beginning of treatment and will be administered only after the EOT visit and establishment of PET

1264

negativity. The decision to administer IV CNS prophylaxis must be determined during the

1265

screening period and prespecified and recorded in the eCRF. In any other case, IV CNS

1266

prophylaxis will be considered a new-anti-lymphoma therapy.

1267

Prophylactic IV treatment is not permitted during the course of the study treatment period.

1268

6.11.2.2 Infection Prophylaxis

1269

Investigators may use their discretion in administering infection prophylaxis in patients

1270

participating in this study.

1271

For Participants considered to be at high risk (chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, history of

1272

prior fungal infection, 60 and above years of age, chronic cardiovascular disease, inpatient status),

1273

infection prophylaxis (including but not limited to acyclovir or similar drug for herpes zoster and

1274

trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole for Pneumocystis jirovecii infection) should be considered.

1275

Bacterial prophylaxis with fluoroquinolone during neutropenia in high-risk participants should be

1276

considered. For patients who are intolerant to fluoroquinolone, consider an oral third-generation

1277

cephalosporin.

1278

Monitoring of participants for fever, neutropenia and infections and treatment with appropriate

1279

anti-infective therapy should be instituted as clinically indicated.

1280

6.11.2.3 Nausea Prophylaxis

1281

Premedication with an antiemetic is recommended according to local practice. Intensification of

1282

prophylaxis with combinations of antiemetics is recommended in order to achieve full antiemetic

1283

effect.

1284

6.11.2.4 Pre-specified Consolidation Treatment

1285

The investigator may prospectively choose to give local radiotherapy after study chemotherapy for

1286

the treatment of a particular site of bulky disease or a large mass. In the case of consolidation

1287

treatment, bulky disease is defined as ≥ 7.0 cm. However, the decision to treat and the location to

1288

be treated must be determined during the screening period and prespecified and recorded in the

1289

eCRF. In this case, the consolidation radiotherapy will not count as a new anti-lymphoma therapy

1290

event for the event-free survival (EFS) endpoint.

1291

If the investigator should decide at any time after Cycle 1 Day 1 to give consolidation treatment,

1292

or to switch treatment to a different lesion, receipt of consolidation treatment will count as a new-

1293

anti-lymphoma therapy and an EFS event.

1294

1295

7 PARTICIPANT DISCONTINUATION OF TRIAL INTERVENTION

1296

AND DISCONTINUATION OR WITHDRAWAL FROM TRIAL

1297

7.1 Discontinuation of Trial Intervention for Individual Participants

1298

7.1.1 Permanent Discontinuation of Trial Intervention

1299

Participants MUST discontinue IP/IMP (and Non-IMP/AxMP at the discretion of the investigator)

1300

for any of the following reasons:

1301

Participant’s request to stop study intervention.

1302

Any clinical AE, laboratory test result abnormality, or intercurrent illness that, in the opinion of

1303

the investigator, indicates that continued participation in the study is not in the best interest of

1304

the participant.

1305

Termination of the study by the Sponsor.

1306

Loss of ability to freely provide consent through imprisonment or involuntary incarceration for

1307

treatment of either a psychiatric or physical illness (eg, infectious disease). (Note: Under

1308

specific circumstances and only in countries where local regulations permit, a participant who

1309

has been imprisoned may be permitted to continue the study. Strict conditions apply, and

1310

Sponsor approval is required.)

1311

Pregnancy

1312

Death

1313

Disease progression per investigator, based on the Lugano response criteria59 (Appendix 9)

1314

Patient noncompliance with protocol per Investigator’s judgment. Such cases should be discussed

1315

with the Medical Monitor.

1316

All participants who discontinue study intervention should comply with protocol-specified

1317

procedures as outlined in Section 2 Schedule of Activities for an end of treatment/early termination

1318

visit and should continue in the study for subsequent follow-up. The only exception is when a

1319

participant withdraws consent for all study procedures, including post-treatment study follow-up,

1320

or loses the ability to consent freely (eg, is imprisoned or involuntarily incarcerated for the

1321

treatment of either a psychiatric or physical illness).

1322

If study intervention is discontinued prior to the participant’s completion of the study, the reason

1323

for the discontinuation must be documented in the participant’s medical records per local

1324

regulatory requirements in each region/country and entered on the appropriate CRF page.

1325

Participants who discontinue study intervention prior to the participant’s completion of the study

1326

will not be replaced.

1327 7.1.2 Temporary Discontinuation of Trial Intervention

1328

Participants may withdraw completely from the study at any time at their own request or may be

1329

withdrawn at any time at the discretion of the investigator for safety, behavioral, compliance, or

1330

administrative reasons. Stopping study intervention is not considered withdrawal from the study.

1331

At the time of discontinuing from the study, if possible, an early termination visit should be

1332

conducted, as shown in Section 2 Schedule of Activities. See the Schedule of Activities for data

1333

to be collected at the time of study discontinuation and follow-up, if applicable, and for any further

1334

evaluations that need to be completed.

1335

The participant will be permanently discontinued from both the study intervention and the study

1336

at that time.

1337

If the participant withdraws consent for disclosure of future information, the Sponsor may retain

1338

and continue to use any data collected before such a withdrawal of consent.

1339

7.1.3 Rechallenge

1340

Not applicable

1341

7.2 Participant Discontinuation or Withdrawal from the Trial

1342

Participants should notify the investigator of the decision to withdraw consent from future follow-

1343

up.

1344

The withdrawal of consent should be explained in detail in the medical records by the investigator

1345

as to whether the withdrawal is from further treatment with study intervention only or also

1346

from study procedures and/or post-treatment study follow-up, and entered on the appropriate

1347

CRF page.

1348

If vital status (whether the participant is alive or dead) is being measured, publicly available

1349

information should be used to determine vital status only as appropriately directed in

1350

accordance with local law.

1351

If the participant withdraws consent for disclosure of future information, the Sponsor may retain

1352

and continue to use any data collected before such a withdrawal of consent.

1353

Death

1354

Lost to follow-up

1355

Study termination by Sponsor or site closure

1356

7.3 Lost to Follow-Up

1357

The following actions must be taken if a participant fails to return to the clinic for a required

1358

study visit:

1359

All reasonable efforts must be made to locate participants to determine and report their ongoing

1360

status. This includes follow-up with persons authorized by the participant.

1361

Lost to follow-up is defined by the inability to reach the participant after a minimum

1362

of 3 documented phone calls, faxes, or emails, as well as lack of response by participant

1363

to 1 registered mail letter. All attempts should be documented in the participant’s

1364

medical records.

1365

If the investigator’s use of a third-party representative to assist in the follow-up portion of the study

1366

has been included in the participant’s informed consent, then the investigator may use a

1367

Sponsor-retained third-party representative to assist site staff with obtaining the participant’s

1368

contact information or other public vital status data, such as public health registries and

1369

databases, necessary to complete the follow-up portion of the study.

1370

The site staff and representative will consult publicly available sources, such as public health

1371

registries and databases, to obtain updated contact information.

1372

If, after all attempts, the participant remains lost to follow-up, then the last known alive date as

1373

determined by the investigator should be reported and documented in the participant’s medical

1374

records.

1375

If it is determined that the participant has died, the site will use permissible local methods to obtain

1376

date and cause of death.

1377

8 TRIAL ASSESSMENTS AND PROCEDURES

1378

8.1 Trial Assessments and Procedures Considerations

1379

Study procedures and timing are summarized in Section 2 Schedule of Activities.

1380

Protocol waivers or exemptions are not allowed.

1381

All immediate safety concerns must be discussed with the Sponsor immediately upon occurrence

1382

or awareness to determine whether the participant should continue or discontinue treatment.

1383

All screening evaluations must be completed and reviewed within 28 days prior to first dose of

1384

study treatment to confirm that potential participants meet all eligibility criteria before

1385

randomization. The investigator will maintain a screening log to record details of all

1386

participants screened and to confirm eligibility or record reasons for screening failure, as

1387

applicable.

1388

Procedures conducted as part of the participant’s routine clinical management (eg, complete blood

1389

count) and obtained before signing of informed consent may be utilized for screening or

1390

baseline purposes provided the procedure meets the protocol-defined criteria and has been

1391

performed within the time frame defined in the Schedule of Activities.

1392

Repeat or unscheduled samples may be taken for safety reasons or for technical issues with the

1393

samples and results should be documented in appropriate eCRFs.

1394

Recorded measurements will be captured in the source document and eCRF.

1395

Unscheduled assessments should be performed as clinically indicated. Procedures conducted

1396

during unscheduled visits should be recorded in the participant’s source documents and in the

1397

appropriate eCRFs.

1398

8.2 Screening/Baseline Assessments and Procedures

1399

1400

8.3 Efficacy Assessments and Procedures

1401

Disease response will be assessed using Lugano 2014 classification (Appendix 9) at time points

1402

detailed in the Schedule of Activities (Section 2).

1403

Imaging will be performed at the following time points:

1404

Screening: Integrated whole-body PET-CT scan (top-of-head to mid-thighs) or separate PET and

1405

CT covering the neck, chest, abdomen, pelvis, and all known/suspected sites of disease. Tumor

1406

assessments previously acquired as SOC within 56 days prior to C1D1 may be used to fulfill

1407

the imaging screening requirement.

1408

Interim assessment at Cycle 4 Day 1 (CT or FDG-PET-CT per institutional practice; FDG-PET

1409

preferred. MRI is allowed.)

1410

At any time during the study treatment period upon clinical indication.

1411

EOT efficacy follow-up: Six to 8 weeks from last dose. FDG-PET-CT or separate PET and CT

1412

covering all known/suspected sites of disease. Use of CT alone for the EOT assessment is not

1413

acceptable.

1414

Long-term follow-up: CT scans according to Section 2: Schedule of Activities. Time points at 12

1415

months, 18, months, 24, months, 36, months, 48 months, and 60 months are from date of

1416

randomization.

1417

MRI instead of CT is allowed during follow-up; however, a consistent use of the same imaging

1418

modality is strongly recommended during the entire duration of the trial.

1419

committee. In case of investigator assessed progression based on CT/MRI at any point during the

1420

study, a confirmatory FDG-PET has to be performed within 14 days to confirm progression.

1421

Imaging efficacy assessment performed by the sites for study participants will stop in the following

1422

scenarios: Upon confirmed progression per investigator, upon death or withdrawal of consent, or

1423

end of study. Scheduled imaging efficacy assessments during follow-up should continue in case

1424

of start of subsequent anti-lymphoma therapy in absence of investigator assessed progression, if

1425

clinically feasible.

1426

At all times during the study, diagnosis of disease progression based on clinical examination

1427

must be confirmed by imaging (eg, CT, MRI, or PET-CT) as soon as feasible (within 28 days)

1428

and prior to initiation of non–protocol-specified anti-lymphoma therapy.

1429

8.3.1 Post-treatment Follow-up for Subsequent Progressions, Therapies, and Overall

1430

Survival

1431

In this study, PFS2 and overall survival are secondary efficacy endpoints. Post-study follow-up is

1432

of critical importance and is essential to preserving participant safety and the integrity of the study.

1433

Participants who complete study treatment or discontinue study treatment prematurely must

1434

continue to be followed for collection of first progression. After the first disease progression or

1435

first unplanned anti-lymphoma therapy is documented, all participants must be followed for

1436

subsequent progressions, subsequent anti-lymphoma therapies, and overall survival (OS), until the

1437

target 265 PFS events have been accrued or the last randomized patient has been followed for at

1438

least 3 years from the last dose of treatment, whichever occurs later.

1439

Every effort should be made by the sites to minimize missing data related to efficacy outcomes in

1440

the follow-up period, including:

1441
  • Collection of date and cause of death by using publicly available information in accordance

1442

with local law.

1443
  • During the long-term follow-up period, record views, phone visits, and home visits (where

1444

applicable) are allowed at the investigator’s discretion and judgment.

1445

8.3.2 Independent Response Adjudication Committee (IRAC)

1446

Images will be submitted to an Independent Response Adjudication Committee (IRAC) for blinded

1447

independent central review at any time during the study. Prior to scanning the first participant,

1448

sites should be qualified and understand the image acquisition guidelines and submission process

1449

as outlined in the Imaging Manual provided by the central imaging vendor.

1450

Both the screening and expected on-study images should be acquired as outlined in Section 2

1451

Schedule of Activities. Any additional FDG-PET-CT or CT/MR images performed either at

1452

unscheduled timepoints and/or at an outside institution, which may demonstrate tumor response

1453

or progression per Lugano, should be submitted to the central imaging vendor.

1454

Pathology reports of biopsies performed during treatment or in follow-up study period confirming

1455

or disproving disease relapse/progression or presence of residual disease should also be sent to the

1456

central imaging vendor.

1457

IRAC will review all scans and relevant clinical data for efficacy assessment using the Lugano

1458

response criteria.59 IRAC’s assessment will be the basis for the secondary endpoint of PFS, which

1459

will serve as a sensitivity analysis for the primary PFS endpoint per Investigator. The

1460

responsibilities, composition, and functions of the IRAC will be outlined in the Imaging Manual.

1461

IRAC members will be blinded to treatment assignment.

1462

While assessment by IRAC will ensure consistency and minimize variability across radiologists

1463

and sites, its review will be performed sometime after image submission by site. All real-time

1464

radiologic eligibility and response assessments guiding enrollment and treatment decisions will be

1465

performed locally at the responsibility of the Investigator.

1466

8.3.2.1 Methods of Assessment

1467

Primary response assessment will be made using Lugano 2014 classification (Appendix 9).

1468

For CT-based assessment, contrast-enhanced CT of the neck, chest, abdomen, pelvis, and all other

1469

known and/or suspected sites of disease should be acquired consistently. Assessment of the spleen

1470

size using CT/MRI should be included in the overall Lugano assessment; see Appendix 9 for

1471

details.

1472

Tumor measurements should be made by the same investigator or radiologist for each assessment,

1473

whenever possible. In case of a contraindication for either contrast agent or MRI (eg, incompatible

1474

pacemaker), it is strongly recommended to use the following guidance:

1475

If a participant has a contraindication for CT intravenous contrast, then a non-contrast CT of the

1476

chest and a contrast-enhanced MRI of the abdomen, pelvis, and other known/suspected sites of

1477

disease should be obtained.

1478

If a participant has a contraindication for both MRI and CT intravenous contrasts, then a non-

1479

contrast CT of the chest and a non-contrast MRI of the abdomen, pelvis, and other

1480

known/suspected sites of disease should be obtained.

1481

If a participant has a contraindication for MRI in addition to contraindication to CT intravenous

1482

contrast, then a non-contrast CT of the chest, abdomen, pelvis, and other known/suspected sites of

1483

disease is acceptable. MRI of the brain (without and with contrast) should be acquired when

1484

clinically indicated. CT of the brain (without and with contrast) can be performed if MRI is

1485

contraindicated.

1486

8.3.2.2 Bone Marrow Biopsy

1487

Bone marrow evaluation will be performed during screening, except for participants with

1488

confirmed bone marrow involvement by FDG-PET scan analysis. Preferred methodology (biopsy

1489

and/or aspirate) will be determined by the investigator, following published and/or local

1490

guidelines.

1491

Note: If a bone marrow sample was collected 90 days prior to Cycle 1 Day 1, that sample can be

1492

used for the required screening sample.

1493

Bone marrow evaluation is required for confirmation of a CR, except in participants with no

1494

evidence of lymphomatous marrow involvement on bone marrow biopsy performed during

1495

screening. The same modality (biopsy or aspirate) used at screening should be used for all further

1496

assessments of bone marrow involvement. In case of bone marrow involvement diagnosed by

1497

FDG-PET scan only at screening, a bone marrow biopsy and/or aspirate is required to confirm a

1498

CR. Bone marrow assessment at screening should be performed before the initiation of prephase.

1499

However, if the disease is rapidly progressing, bone marrow assessments can be performed in the

1500

days following initiation of prephase.

1501

8.3.3 Clinical Outcomes Assessments

1502

The evaluation of patient-reported outcomes (PROs) is an increasingly important aspect of clinical

1503

efficacy in hematology trials. Such data provide an understanding of the impact of treatment from

1504

the participant’s perspective and offer insights into participant experience that may not be captured

1505

through physician reporting. Additionally, generic health-related quality of life (HRQoL)

1506

measures provide data needed for calculating utility values to inform health economic models.

1507

The PROs (European Organization for Research and Treatment of Cancer – Quality of Life C30

1508

questionnaire [EORTC QLQ-C30], Functional Assessment of Cancer Treatment-Lymphoma

1509

Subscale [FACT-LymS], and the EQ-5D-5L) will be provided to each participant to complete at

1510

screening and subsequent study visits. The PROs will be completed by the participant before any

1511

clinical assessments are performed at any given visit. If a participant refuses to complete a

1512

questionnaire, this may be reported. Participants will complete all PROs via electronic Clinical

1513

Outcome Assessment when deployed at the site. After disease progression, only the EQ-5D-5L

1514

will be collected using a telephone script during OS telephone calls.

1515

Questionnaires should be completed in the language most familiar to each participant, and

1516

participants should be given adequate time and space to complete the questionnaire. If the

1517

participant withdraws from the study prematurely, all attempts should be made to obtain final

1518

Clinical Outcome Assessment prior to participant discontinuation. If exceptional circumstances

1519

preclude the continued administration of measures using planned modalities, then alternate

1520

administration methods may be required.

1521

PRO collection for all participants will continue until the last timepoint per Section 2 or until the

1522

time of primary analysis and study unblinding, whichever occurs first.

1523

8.3.3.1 EORTC QLQ C30

1524

The European Organization for Research and Treatment of Cancer – Quality of Life C30

1525

Questionnaire 36 (EORTC QLQ-C30) questionnaire will be used as a measure of health-related

35F

1526

quality of life (Appendix 12). The EORTC QLQ-C30 is composed of both multi-item scales and

1527

single-item measures. These include five functional scales (physical, role, emotional, cognitive,

1528

and social), three symptom scales (fatigue, nausea/vomiting, and pain), a global health

1529

status/health-related quality of life (HRQoL) scale, and six single items (dyspnea, insomnia,

1530

appetite loss, constipation, diarrhea, and financial difficulties). Global health status/quality of life,

1531

physical functioning, role functioning, cognitive functioning, fatigue, and pain will be evaluated

1532

as primary domains as they are considered the most clinically relevant and important concepts to

1533

measure for the patient population (FDA Draft Guidance, 2021). The remaining will be assessed

1534

as exploratory domains.

1535

Each of the multi-item scales includes a different set of items – no item occurs in more than one

1536

scale. The EORTC QLQ-C30 employs a week recall period for all items and a 4-point scale for

1537

the functional and symptom scales/items with response categories “Not at all”, “A little”, “Quite

1538

a bit” and “Very much”. The two items assessing global health status/ HRQoL utilize a 7-point

1539

scale ranging from 1 (“Very Poor”) to 7 (“Excellent”).

1540

8.3.3.2 FACT-LymS

1541

Lymphoma specific symptoms will be assessed using the FACT-LymS, a lymphoma specific

1542

subscale of the Functional Assessment of Cancer Treatment-Lymphoma (FACT-Lym) measure.

1543

FACT-LymS is a 15-item lymphoma-specific additional concerns subscale (Appendix 13). This

1544

subscale addresses symptoms and functional limitations that are important to lymphoma patients.

1545

The FACT-LymS items are scored on a 0 (“Not at all”) to 4 (“Very much”) response scale. Items

1546

are aggregated to a single score on a 0-60 scale. High scores indicate lower symptom burden.

1547

Although FACT-LymS was initially designed to be administered in conjunction with the FACT-

1548

Lym entire scale, its independent psychometric characteristics were validated as a separate

1549

assessment tool 37; and the subscale demonstrated good psychometric characteristics and ability to

36F

1550

distinguish changes among lymphoma patients.

1551

8.3.3.3 EQ-5D-5L

1552

The EQ-5D-5L is a generic, self-reported preference-based measure of health outcome that is

1553

applicable to a wide range of health conditions and treatments (Appendix 14). 38 The EQ-5D-5L

37F

1554

consists of a descriptive system scale and a visual anolog scale (VAS). The descriptive system includes

1555

5 items measuring functioning and well-being across 5 dimensions: mobility, self-care,

1556

pain/discomfort, usual activities, and anxiety/depression. Each of these dimensions comprise 5 levels

1557

of severity: “no problems,” “slight problems,” “moderate problems,” “severe problems,” and “unable

1558

to do/extreme problems.” A unique EQ-5D-5L health state (ie, health state preference) is defined by

1559

combining one level or response option from each of the 5 dimensions. Responses to the 5 items are

1560

then converted to a weighted health state index (utility score) by either cross-walking to country-

1561

specific EQ-5D-3L value sets or based on values derived from country specific general population

1562

samples directly for the EQ-5D-5L (ie, country specific value sets). The EQ-VAS records the

1563

respondent’s self-rated current health status on a vertical, 0 to 100 scale, where 100 = “best

1564

imaginable health state” and 0 = “worst imaginable health state.” This information can be used as

1565

a quantitative measure of health outcome as judged by the individual respondents. A telephone

1566

script will be used for sites to administer the measure via telephone during the OS phase.

1567

1568

1569

A physical examination includes assessment of lymph nodes, spleen, liver, heart, lungs, abdomen,

1570

neurological status, and skin. The exam is performed at screening, on treatment, and in the follow-

1571

up phase as indicated in Section 2. If a scheduled or unscheduled physical examination assessment

1572

was performed within 7 days prior to the end of treatment visit, the assessment does not need to

1573

1574

1575

up period.

1576

Refer to Section 2: Schedule of Activities for details on the timepoints for assessment to be

1577

1579

1580

treatment, and in the follow-up phase as indicated in Section 2. If a scheduled or unscheduled vital

1581

sign assessment was performed within 7 days prior to the end of treatment visit, the assessment

1582

does not need to be repeated again at the end of treatment visit.

1583

1586

1587

1588

used to fulfill the eligibility requirement. 12-lead ECGs may be performed during study treatment

1589

as clinically indicated.

1590

1591

performed.

1593

1594

1596

1597

1598

1599 8.4.5 Pregnancy Testing

1600

A pregnancy test is required for all IOCBP and should be performed per the Pregnancy Prevention

1601

Plan (Appendix 4). Serum beta subunit of human chorionic gonadotropin pregnancy test (with a

1602

sensitivity of at least 25 mIU/mL) must be performed locally at screening within 10 to 14 days

1603

prior to the start of study treatment. The second urine (or serum) pregnancy test will be performed

1604

locally to assess subject eligibility within 24 hours prior to the first administration of study

1605

treatment.

1606

Females of childbearing potential with regular or no menstrual cycles must agree to have

1607

1608

1609

following the last dose of golcadomide.

1610

Females of childbearing potential with irregular menstrual cycles must agree to have pregnancy

1611

test weekly for the first 28 days of study participation and then every 14 days while taking

1612

1613

golcadomide.

1614

If urgent treatment is needed and requires a shorter window of screening, please contact the

1615

medical monitor immediately.

1617

1619

Any incidental findings of potential clinical relevance that are not directly associated with the

1620

objectives of the protocol should be evaluated and handled by the study investigator per standard

1621

medical/clinical judgment.

9.1

Definitions

1733

9.1.1

Definitions of Adverse Events

1734

An adverse event (AE) is defined as any new untoward medical occurrence or worsening of a pre-

1735

existing medical condition occurring in a clinical investigation participant after signing of

1736

informed consent, whether or not considered related to the study intervention. An AE can therefore

1737

be any unfavorable and unintended sign (such as an abnormal laboratory test result), symptom, or

1738

disease temporally associated with the study intervention.

1739

Events Meeting the AE Definition

1740
  • Any abnormal laboratory test results (hematology, clinical chemistry, or urinalysis) or results

1741

from other safety assessments (eg, electrocardiograms, radiological scans, vital sign

1742

measurements), including those that worsen from baseline, considered clinically significant in

1743

the medical and scientific judgment of the investigator. Note that abnormal laboratory test

1744

results or other safety assessment findings should only be reported as AEs if the final diagnosis

1745

is not available. Once the final diagnosis is known, the reported term should be updated to be

1746

the diagnosis.

1747
  • Exacerbation of a chronic or intermittent pre-existing condition, including either an increase

1748

in frequency and/or intensity of the condition.

1749
  • New conditions detected or diagnosed after study intervention administration, even though the

1750

condition may have been present before the start of the study.

1751
  • Signs, symptoms, or the clinical sequelae of a suspected drug-drug interaction.

1752
  • Signs, symptoms, or the clinical sequelae of a suspected overdose of either study intervention

1753

or a concomitant medication. Overdose, as a verbatim term (as reported by the investigator),

1754

should not be reported as an AE/serious adverse event (SAE) unless it is an intentional

1755

overdose taken with possible suicidal/self-harming intent. Such overdoses should be reported

1756

regardless of sequelae and should specify “intentional overdose” as the verbatim term.

1757

Events not Meeting the AE Definition

1758
  • Medical or surgical procedure (eg, endoscopy, appendectomy); the condition that leads to the

1759

procedure is the AE.

1760
  • Situations in which an untoward medical occurrence did not occur (social and/or convenience

1761

admission to a hospital).

1762

9.1.2 Definitions of Serious Adverse Events

1763

If an event is not an AE per the definition above, then it cannot be an SAE, even if serious

1764

conditions are met.

1765

A SAE is defined as any untoward medical occurrence that, at any dose:

1766
  • Results in death

1767
  • Is life threatening (defined as an event in which the participant was at risk of death at the time

1768

of the event; it does not refer to an event that hypothetically might have caused death if it were

1769

more severe).

1770
  • Requires inpatient hospitalization or causes prolongation of existing hospitalization (see Notes

1771

below).

1772

Note: The following hospitalizations are not considered SAEs in BMS clinical studies:

1773
  • A visit to the emergency department or other hospital department that does not result in

1774

admission. These visits should be evaluated for an occurrence of 1 of the other serious

1775

outcomes that would qualify as an SAE.

1776
  • Elective surgery that was planned prior to signing consent.

1777
  • Admissions per protocol for a planned medical/surgical procedure.

1778

1779
  • Routine health assessment requiring admission for baseline/trending of health status (eg, routine colonoscopy).

1780
  • Medical/surgical admission other than to remedy ill health and planned prior to enrollment in

1781

the study. Appropriate documentation is required in these cases.

1782
  • Admission encountered for another life circumstance that carries no bearing on health status

1783

and requires no medical/surgical intervention (eg, lack of housing, economic inadequacy,

1784

caregiver respite, family circumstances, administrative reason).

1785
  • Admission for administration of anticancer therapy in the absence of any other SAEs (applies

1786

to oncology protocols).

1787
  • Results in persistent or significant disability/incapacity

1788
  • Is a congenital anomaly/birth defect

1789

Is an important medical event (defined as a medical event[s] that may not be immediately life

1790

threatening or results in death or hospitalization but, based upon appropriate medical and scientific

1791

judgment, may jeopardize the participant or may require intervention [eg, medical, surgical] to

1792

prevent one of the other serious outcomes listed in the definition above). Examples of such events

1793

include, but are not limited to, intensive treatment in an emergency department or at home for

1794

allergic bronchospasm and blood dyscrasias or convulsions that do not result in hospitalization.

1795

Potential drug-induced liver injury (DILI) is also considered an important medical event.

1796

Events NOT meeting the SAE definition:

1797
  • A standard procedure for protocol therapy administration. However, hospitalization or

1798

prolonged hospitalization for a complication of therapy administration will be reported as an

1799

SAE.

1800
  • Routine treatment or monitoring of the studied indication not associated with any deterioration

1801

in condition.

1802
  • The administration of blood or platelet transfusion as routine treatment of studied indication.

1803

However, hospitalization or prolonged hospitalization for a complication of such transfusion

1804

remains a reportable SAE.

1805
  • A procedure for protocol/disease-related investigations (eg, surgery, scans, endoscopy,

1806

sampling for laboratory tests, bone marrow sampling). However, hospitalization or prolonged

1807

hospitalization for a complication of such procedures remains a reportable SAE.

1808
  • Hospitalization or prolongation of hospitalization for technical, practical, or social reasons, in

1809

absence of an AE.

1810
  • A procedure that is planned (ie, planned prior to start of treatment on study); must be

1811

documented in the source document and the CRF. Hospitalization or prolonged hospitalization

1812

for a complication remains a reportable SAE.

1813
  • An elective treatment of or an elective procedure for a pre-existing condition, unrelated to the

1814

studied indication, that has not worsened from baseline.

1815
  • Emergency outpatient treatment or observation that does not result in admission, unless

1816

fulfilling other seriousness criteria above.

1817
