9.2 Timing and Procedures for Collection and Reporting

1820

Pregnancy and DILI must follow the same transmission timing and processes to BMS as those

1821

used for SAEs.

1822

9.2.1 Timing

1823

All AEs and SAEs must be collected from the time of signing the informed consent form, including

1824

those thought to be associated with protocol-specified procedures and until 28 days or following

1825

discontinuation of dosing.

1826

The investigator must report any SAE that occurs after these periods and that is believed to be

1827

related to a study intervention or protocol-specified procedure (eg, a follow-up procedure).

1828
  • Medical occurrences that begin before the start of study intervention but after obtaining

1829

informed consent will be recorded on the appropriate section of the CRF module.

1830
  • All SAEs will be recorded and reported to the Sponsor or designee promptly and not to exceed

1831

24 hours of awareness of the event, as indicated in Appendix 3.

1832
  • The investigator will submit any updated SAE data to the Sponsor or designee promptly and

1833

not to exceed 24 hours of updated information being available.

1834

Investigators are not obligated to actively seek AEs or SAEs in former study participants.

1835

However, if the investigator learns of any SAE, including a death, at any time after a participant

1836

has been discharged from the study, and he/she considers the event reasonably related to the study

1837

intervention or study participation, the investigator must promptly notify the Sponsor.

1838

9.2.2 Identification and Assessment

1839

Identification

1840

AEs will be reported by the participant (or, when appropriate, by a caregiver, or a surrogate).

1841

AEs can be spontaneously reported or elicited during open-ended questioning, examination, or

1842

evaluation of a participant. Care should be taken not to introduce bias when collecting AEs and/or

1843

SAEs. Inquiry about specific AEs should be guided by clinical judgment in the context of known

1844

AEs, when appropriate for the program or protocol.

1845

The investigator and any qualified designees are responsible for detecting, documenting, and

1846

reporting events that meet the definition of an AE or SAE and remain responsible for following up

1847

on AEs that are serious, considered related to the study intervention or the study, or that caused

1848

the participant to discontinue before completing the study.

1849

Assessment of Causality

1850
  • The investigator is obligated to assess the relationship between study intervention and each

1851

occurrence of each AE/SAE.

1852
  • A “reasonable possibility” of a relationship conveys that there are facts, evidence, and/or

1853

arguments to suggest a causal relationship, rather than a relationship cannot be ruled out.

1854
  • The investigator will use clinical judgment to determine the relationship.

1855
  • Alternative causes, such as underlying disease(s), concomitant therapy, and other risk factors,

1856

as well as the temporal relationship of the event to study intervention administration, will be

1857

considered and investigated.

1858
  • The investigator will also consult the Investigator’s Brochure and/or product information for

1859

marketed products, in his/her assessment.

1860
  • For each AE/SAE, the investigator must document in the medical notes that he/she has

1861

reviewed the AE/SAE and has provided an assessment of causality.

1862
  • There may be situations in which an SAE has been reported and the investigator has minimal

1863

information to include in the initial report to the Sponsor. However, it is very important that

1864

the investigator always make an assessment of causality for every event before the initial

1865

transmission of the SAE data to the Sponsor.

1866
  • The investigator may change his/her opinion of causality in light of follow-up information and

1867

send an SAE follow-up report with the updated causality assessment.

1868
  • The causality assessment is 1 of the criteria used when determining regulatory reporting

1869

requirements.

1870

Assessment of Intensity

1871

In Cohort A, United States Food and Drug Administration Guidance entitled Toxicity Grading

1872

Scale for Healthy Adult and Adolescent Volunteers Enrolled in Preventative Vaccine Clinical

1873

Trials, and in Cohort B, Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events (CTCAE) v5.0

1874

definitions and grading, will be used for safety reporting of all AE and SAEs on the eCRF.

1875

The investigator will make an assessment of intensity for each AE and SAE reported during the

1876

study and assign it to 1 of the following categories:

1877
  • Mild: An event that is easily tolerated by the participant, causing minimal discomfort, and not

1878

interfering with everyday activities.

1879
  • Moderate: An event that causes sufficient discomfort and interferes with normal everyday

1880

activities.

1881
  • Severe: An event that prevents normal everyday activities. An AE that is assessed as severe

1882

should not be confused with an SAE. Severe is a category utilized for rating the intensity of an

1883

event, and both AEs and SAEs can be assessed as severe.

1884

An event is defined as “serious” when it meets at least 1 of the pre-defined outcomes as described

1885

in the definition of an SAE, NOT when it is rated as severe.

1886

9.2.3 Follow-up

1887

Non-serious AEs should be followed to resolution or stabilization or reported as SAEs if they

1888

become serious.

1889

Follow-up is also required for non-serious AEs that cause interruption or discontinuation of study

1890

intervention and for those present at the end of study intervention as appropriate.

1891

All identified non-serious AEs must be recorded and described on the non-serious AE page of the

1892

CRF (paper or electronic). Completion of supplemental CRFs may be requested for AEs and/or

1893

laboratory test result abnormalities that are reported/identified during the study.

1894

All SAEs will be followed until resolution, until the condition stabilizes, until the event is

1895

otherwise explained, or until the participant is lost to follow-up.

1896

If only limited information is initially available, follow-up reports are required. (Note: Follow-up

1897

SAE reports must include the same investigator term[s] initially reported.)

1898

If an ongoing SAE changes in its intensity or relationship to study intervention or if new

1899

information becomes available, the SAE report must be updated and submitted promptly and not

1900

to exceed 24 hours to BMS (or designee) using the same procedure used for transmitting the initial

1901

SAE report.

1902

All AEs/SAEs must be followed to resolution or stabilization.

1903

9.3 Reporting

1904

SAEs, whether related or not related to study intervention, and pregnancies must be reported to

1905

BMS (or the designee) promptly and not to exceed 24 hours of awareness of the event.

1906

The required method for SAE data reporting is through the electronic Case Report Form (eCRF).

1907

Note: The paper SAE Report Form is intended only as a back-up option when the electronic data

1908

capture system is unavailable/not functioning for transmission of the eCRF to BMS (or the

1909

designee).

1910
  • In this case, the paper form is transmitted via email or confirmed fax transmission.

1911
  • When paper forms are used, the original paper forms are to remain on site.

1912

Pregnancies must be recorded on paper Pregnancy Surveillance Forms and transmitted via email

1913

or confirmed fax transmission.

1914

9.3.1 Regulatory Reporting Requirements

1915
  • Prompt notification by the investigator to the Sponsor of SAEs is essential so that legal

1916

obligations and ethical responsibilities toward the safety of participants and the safety of a

1917

product under clinical investigation are met.

1918
  • An investigator who receives an investigator safety report describing SAEs or other

1919

specific safety information (eg, summary or listing of SAEs) from the Sponsor will file it

1920

along with the Investigator’s Brochure and will notify the IRB/IEC, if appropriate,

1921

according to local requirements.

1922

The Sponsor or designee must report AEs to regulatory authorities and ethics committees

1923

according to local applicable laws and regulations. A suspected, unexpected serious adverse

1924

reaction (SUSAR) is a subset of SAEs and must be reported to the appropriate regulatory

1925

authorities and investigators following local and global guidelines and requirements.

1926

In Cohort A, the FDA guidance entitled Toxicity Grading Scale for Healthy Adult and Adolescent

1927

Volunteers Enrolled in Preventative Vaccine Clinical Trials, and in Cohort B, CTCAE v5.0

1928

definitions and grading, will be used for safety reporting of all AE and SAEs on the eCRF.

participate.

activities on key-coded health data transferred by BMS across national borders is done in

under the data protection laws. To align with the recommended security standards, BMS has

its processing.

12.10 Blood Biomarker Substudy

2608

The goal of the Blood Biomarker Substudy is to generate data on the degradation of neosubstrates

2609

of golcadomide in the context of the CA0731020 trial.

2610

Rationale

2611

Ikaros and Aiolos are neosubstrates for golcadomide. Degradation of Ikaros and Aiolos is central

2612

to golcadomide’s mechanism of action in both tumor and immune cells. Ikaros and Aiolos

2613

degradation has been observed in the peripheral blood T and B cells in Studies CC-99282-NHL-

2614

001 and CC-220-DLBCL-001. The level of neosubstrate degradation was related to golcadomide

2615

dose and exposure. By measuring Ikaros and Aiolos degradation in this substudy of CA0731020,

2616

the degradation of Ikaros and Aiolos at steady-state concentrations of golcadomide and the

2617

recovery after a drug holiday will be confirmed in a high-risk DLBCL population. Ikaros and

2618

Aiolos kinetics resulting from golcadomide treatment can also directly be compared to a placebo

2619

control.

2620

Study Design and Assessments

2621

Ikaros and Aiolos analysis from blood is nested in the main study and will be performed on patients

2622

at selected sites from both the golcadomide + R-CHOP and the placebo + R-CHOP arms. Blood

2623

will be drawn on C1D1, C1D8 and C2D1; for C1D1 and C2D1, blood will be drawn prior to

2624

treatment. Ikaros and Aiolos levels will be measured in T and B cells using flow cytometry. The

2625

details of blood collection, sample shipment and sample processing will be in the laboratory

2626

manual.

2627

Aims of Peripheral Blood Collection for this Substudy

2628

This biomarker substudy will accomplish the following:

2629

1) Determine the reduction in Ikaros and Aiolos levels at steady-state concentrations of

2630

golcadomide in high-risk DLBCL patients.

2631

2) Evaluate the recovery of Ikaros and Aiolos towards baseline at the beginning of Cycle 2.

2632

3) Directly compare Ikaros and Aiolos dynamics from golcadomide treatment versus a placebo

2633

control

2634

Objectives and Endpoints

2635

Exploratory objectives related to Ikaros and Aiolos will be listed in the main study. Analyses of

2636

Ikaros and Aiolos will be detailed in the SAP and biomarker SAP.

2637

Study Population

2638

Approximately 50 subjects participating in the CA0731020 study will be selected for the blood

2639

biomarker substudy. Subjects are not required to enroll in the substudy to participate in the main

2640

CA0731020 study. Since this study is blinded and arms are 1:1 randomized, approximately 25

2641

subjects will be from the golcadomide + R-CHOP arm and another 25 will be from the placebo +

2642

R-CHOP arm. Patients must have appropriate performance status per Investigator’s judgement and

2643

institutional guidelines. Participants must sign a separate sub-study ICF to enroll in the Blood

2644

Biomarker sub-study before any sampling is performed, in addition to the ICF required for the

2645

2647

study. Withdrawal from the Blood Biomarker Substudy will not impact participation in the main study.
